{"parse":{"title":"bread","pageid":7381,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"==English==\n{{wp}}\n{{wikibooks|cookbook=bread}}\n[[File:Serbian bread.jpg|thumb|Two [[loaf|loaves]] of bread (1).]]\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/brɛd/|/brɛːd/|a=Early Modern}}<ref>{{R:en:Dobson:1957|II|30|502}}</ref>\n* {{enPR|brĕd|a=RP,GA,CA}}, {{IPA|en|/bɹɛd/}}\n* {{audio|en|En-uk-bread.ogg|a=RP}}\n* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Naomi Persephone Amethyst (NaomiAmethyst)-bread.wav|a=GA}}\n* {{audio|en|En-us-bread.ogg|a=GA}}\n* {{IPA|en|/bɹed/|a=AU,NZ}}\n* {{homophones|en|bred}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɛd|s=1}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymon|en|id=food|:inh|enm:bred|tree=1}}\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*bʰrewh₁-}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|bred}}, {{m|enm|breed}}, from {{inh|en|ang|brēad|t=fragment, bit, morsel, crumb\", also \"bread}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*braud}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*braudą|t=bread}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*bʰrewh₁-|*bʰerw-, *bʰrewh₁-|t=to boil; to brew}}, from {{m|ine-pro|*bʰer-|t=to bear, carry}}. Alternatively, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*braudaz}}, {{m|gem-pro|*brauþaz|t=broken piece, fragment}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*bʰera-|t=to split, beat, hew, struggle}} (see {{l|en|brittle}}). Perhaps a conflation of the two. Possibly a {{doublet|en|broa|nocap=1}}. \n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognate with {{cog|sco|breid|t=bread}}, {{cog|yol|breed|t=bread}}, {{cog|frr|bruad}}, {{m|frr|Bruar}}, {{m|frr|brüüdj|t=bread}}, {{cog|stq|Brood|t=bread}}, {{cog|fy|brea|t=bread}}, {{cog|gsw|brot}}, {{m|gsw|broud}}, {{m|gsw|bruat}}, {{m|gsw|bròt}}, {{m|gsw|bröt|t=bread}}, {{cog|cim|proat}}, {{m|cim|pròat|t=bread}}, {{cog|nl|brood|t=bread}}, {{cog|de|Brot|t=bread}}, {{cog|nds-de|Brod}}, {{m|nds-de|Brood}}, {{m|nds-de|Broot}}, {{m|nds-de|Brot}}, {{m|nds-de|Bräot|t=bread}}, {{cog|li|broed|t=bread}}, {{cog|lb|Brout|t=bread}}, {{cog|mhn|proat|t=bread}}, {{cog|wym|brūt|t=bread; loaf}}, {{cog|yi|ברויט|t=bread}}, {{cog|da,nb|brød|t=bread}}, {{cog|ovd|broð|t=bread}}, {{cog|fo| breyð|t=bread}}, {{cog|is|brauð|t=bread}}, {{cog|nrn|brau}}, {{m|nrn|brow|t=bread}}, {{cog|nn|braud}}, {{m|nn|brød|t=bread}}, {{cog|sv|bröd|t=bread}}, {{cog|gme-cgo|broe|t=bread}}; also {{cog|kw|brys|t=thought; mind}}, {{cog|ga,gd|beir|t=bear, give birth to}}, {{cog|cy|bryd|t=aim, intent}}, {{cog|la|fors|t=chance, luck}}, {{cog|el|φέρνω}}, {{m|el|φέρω|t=to bear, carry}}, {{cog|sq|brydh|t=to ripen, soften; to crumble}}, {{cog|lv|bērt|t=to pour; to scatter, strew}}, {{cog|lt|berti|t=to scatter, strew}}, {{cog|be|бру́ха|t=belly}}, {{cog|cs|břich}}, {{m|cs|břicho}}, {{m|cs|břuch|t=belly}}, {{cog|csb|brzëch|t=belly}}, {{cog|pl|brzuch}}, {{m|pl|brzucho|t=belly}}, {{cog|ru|брю́хо|t=belly}}, {{cog|sk|brucho|t=belly}}, {{cog|hy|բերել|t=to bring, fetch}}, {{cog|fa|بردن|tr=bordan/burdan|t=to bear, carry}}, {{cog|xto,txb|pär-|t=to bear; to wear}}, {{cog|sa|भारयति|t=to carry}}. \n{{col-bottom}}\nEclipsed non-native {{noncog|enm|payn|t=bread}}, borrowed from {{noncog|fro|pain|t=bread}}. In this sense, mostly replaced {{m|en|loaf}}, which had been the more common term in Old English (see {{m|ang|hlaf}}), a process which similarly occured in other languages such as German.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|en|breade||obsolete}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|~}}\n\n# {{lb|en|uncountable}}\n## {{senseid|en|Q7802}} A [[foodstuff]] made by [[bake|baking]] [[dough]] made from [[cereal]]s.\n##: {{hypo|en|tack<id:food, especially bread or breadlike food>|biscuit<id:durable, hard, dry bread or breadlike foodstuff>}}\n### {{lb|en|especially}} Such foodstuff that is not difficult to [[chew#Verb|chew]], being not extremely hard, dense, and dry.\n###: {{cot|en|tack<id:food, especially bread or breadlike food>|biscuit<id:durable, hard, dry bread or breadlike foodstuff>}}\n###: {{ux|en|We made sandwiches with the '''bread''' we bought from the bakery.}}\n###: {{ux|en|My mother used to send me for the '''bread'''.}}\n###* {{RQ:Lincoln Pratt's Patients|chapter=8|passage=Philander went into the next room{{...}}and came back with a salt mackerel that dripped brine like a rainstorm. Then he put the coffee pot on the stove and rummaged out a loaf of dry '''bread''' and some hardtack.}}\n## Food; sustenance; support of life, in general.\n##: {{syn|en|staff of life}}\n##* {{RQ:KJV|Matthew|4|11||Give us this day our daily '''bread'''.}}\n# {{lb|en|countable}} Any variety of bread.\n#: {{ux|en|Some '''breads''' are harder and drier than others.}}\n# {{senseid|en|money}} {{lb|en|slang|US|or|Cockney}} [[money|Money]].\n#: {{syn|en|Thesaurus:money}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1962|year_published=1963|month_published=January|author=w:James Baldwin|title={{w|Another Country (novel)|Another Country}}|location=New York, N. Y.|publisher=w:The Dial Press|pages=3–4|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/anothercountry0000bald/page/4/mode/2up?q=bread|passage=Maybe somebody would see him and recognize him, maybe one of the guys would lay enough '''bread''' on him for a meal or at least subway fare.}}\n#* {{quote-song|en|year=1967|artist=w:Eric Burdon; w:The Animals|album=Winds of Change|title=w:San Franciscan Nights|passage={{...|This is a very personal song, so if the viewer cannot understand it, particularly those of you who are European residents,}} save up all your '''bread''', and fly Trans-Love Airways to San Francisco, USA.}}\n#* {{quote-song|en|year=1973|composer=w:Billy Joel|author=w:Billy Joel|artist=w:Billy Joel|title=[[w:Piano Man (song)|Piano Man]]|passage=And they sit at the bar and put '''bread''' in my jar / And say, \"Man, what are you doing here?\"}}\n#* {{quote-av|en|title=w:Requiem for a Dream|writer=w:Darren Aronofsky; w:Hubert Selby Jr.|year=2000|passage=Hey, baby, I don't care if the motherfucker's growing hair just so long as we get our '''bread'''.|role=Tyrone}}\n#* {{quote-song|en|lyricist=Jordan Houston; Darnell Carlton; Paul Beauregard; Premro Smith; Marlon Goodwin; David Brown; Willie Hutchinson|passage=Tastes like fruit when you hit it; got to have '''bread''' to get it.|url=https://genius.com/Three-6-mafia-stay-fly-lyrics|title=Stay Fly|publisher=Sony BMG|year=2005|album=Most Known Unknown|artist=Three 6 Mafia (featuring Young Buck, 8 Ball, and MJG)}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* [[loaf]], [[slice]], [[piece]], [[hunk]] are some of the words used to count bread.\n\n=====Hyponyms=====\n{{col4|en|aerated bread\n|Afghan bread\n|altar bread|Borodino bread|Borodinski bread|Borodinskii bread|Borodinskiy bread|Borodinsky bread|borodinsky bread|swine's bread\n|Amish friendship bread\n|ammunition bread|milk bread\n|Anadama bread\n|Armenian cracker bread\n|artisan bread\n|banana bread\n|Barbari bread\n|barley bread\n|batter bread\n|beer bread\n|biscuit bread|country bread\n|black bread\n|blackfellow's bread\n|Boston brown bread\n|bread science\n|brown bread\n|bush bread\n|caraway seed bread\n|chub bread\n|ciabatta bread\n|cinnamon bread\n|corn bread\n|cornbread\n|corn rye bread\n|court holy bread\n|cracked-wheat bread\n|cracker bread\n|crisp bread\n|crispbread\n|Cuban bread\n|cuckoo bread\n|curry bread\n|dark bread\n|date bread\n|date-nut bread\n|dika bread\n|dole bread\n|dry bread\n|egg bread\n|eggy bread\n|fairy bread\n|fancy bread\n|flat bread\n|flatbread\n|focaccia bread\n|French bread\n|fried bread\n|fry bread\n|frybread\n|garlic bread\n|gluten bread\n|God's bread\n|Graham bread\n|granary bread\n|Gyeongju bread\n|hard bread\n|hare's bread\n|haver bread\n|heavy bread\n|hog's bread\n|Holy Bread\n|Hottentot bread\n|household bread\n|Hwangnam bread\n|Indian bread\n|Irish soda bread\n|Italian bread\n|Jewish rye bread\n|Kaffir bread\n|kaffir bread\n|lava bread\n|laver bread\n|laverbread\n|light bread\n|limpa bread\n|liquid bread\n|loaf bread\n|Logan bread\n|mandel bread\n|marble rye bread\n|mealie bread\n|melon bread\n|monkey bread\n|monkey's bread\n|native bread\n|new bread\n|nut bread\n|oaten bread\n|olive bread\n|onion bread\n|pan bread\n|pilot bread\n|pita bread\n|pitta bread\n|plain bread\n|pocket bread\n|potato bread\n|potato apple bread\n|Pugliese bread\n|pumpernickel bread\n|pumpkin bread\n|raised bread\n|quick bread\n|raisin bread\n|ravel bread\n|ravelled bread\n|Russian black bread\n|Russian Easter bread\n|rye bread\n|sacramental bread\n|sad bread\n|Saint John's bread\n|St John's bread\n|salt-rising bread\n|sausage bread\n|sea bread\n|Seminole bread\n|shewbread\n|ship bread\n|showbread\n|singing bread\n|skillet bread\n|skillet corn bread\n|sliced bread\n|soda bread\n|sour bread\n|sourbread\n|sourdough bread\n|sowbread\n|spoon bread\n|spoonbread\n|sunflower bread\n|Swedish limpa bread\n|Swedish rye bread\n|sweet bread<!--type of bread-->\n|sweetcorn bread\n|sweet rye bread\n|temse bread\n|temsed bread\n|tiger bread\n|twice-baked bread\n|unleavened bread\n|Veda bread\n|wastel bread\n|wheat bread\n|white bread<!--noun; the adjective \"white-bread\" is derived from this-->\n|whole-grain bread\n|wholegrain bread\n|whole meal bread,whole-meal bread\n|wholemeal bread\n|whole wheat bread\n|whole-wheat bread\n|wholewheat bread\n|yeast bread\n|zaatar bread|famine bread|po' boy bread|showbread\n}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col4|en|bread soup|bread-and-butter plate|hot bread shop|beebread|breadbag|breadcake|breadcraft|breadcrust|breadcutter|breader|breadlike|breadmaker|breadmaking|breadman|breadmonger|breadpill|breadseller|BreadTube|breadwinning|crackerbread|gutbread|nonbread|oatbread\n|a little bit of bread and no cheese|bread and games|bread and roses|bread buckle|bread tab|bread tie|bread-bag|bread-bag clip|logan bread|Bread Book\n|bake someone's bread|bread cheese|have one's bread buttered on both sides\n|below the breadline\n|in bad bread\n|in good bread\n|bee-bread\n|bread and butter|St. John's bread|\n|bread and cheese\n|bread and circuses\n|bread and honey\n|bread and milk\n|bread and salt\n|bread and scrape\n|bread and water\n|bread and wine\n|bread-artist\n|bread bag|butter one's bread and lie in it\n|bread-barge|cloud bread|giraffe bread\n|breadbasket,bread-basket\n|bread-bearer\n|bread beetle|bake bread\n|breadberry,bread-ber